Nigerian insurance industry, meanwhile, grew by 8.01 per cent in 2021, compared to a negative growth rate of 13.29 per cent in 2020. According to NBS, the finance and insurance sector consists of the two sub-sectors, financial institutions and insurance, which accounted for 92.18 per cent and 7.82 per cent of the sector respectively in real terms in Q4 2021. As a whole, it said, the sector grew at 24.92 per cent in nominal terms (year-on-year), with the growth rate of financial institutions as 25.99 per cent and 13.61 per cent growth rate recorded for insurance. Stating that the overall rate was higher than that in Q4 2020 by 26.02 per cent points, and lower by 1.54 per cent points than the preceding quarter, it added that, quarter on quarter growth was 25.34 per cent, while annual growth rate stood at 11.88 per cent in 2021. The sector’s contribution to the overall nominal GDP was 3.10 per cent in Q4 2021, higher than the 2.80 per cent it represented a year previous, and higher from the contribution of 2.70 per cent it made in the preceding quarter. “Growth in this sector in real terms totalled 24.14 per cent, higher by 27.76 per cent points from the rate recorded in 2020 fourth quarter and up by 0.90 per cent points from the rate recorded in the preceding quarter. “Quarter on quarter growth in real terms stood at 26.99 per cent, while annual growth was 10.07 per cent in 2021,” it pointed out. 